COMPUTERS AND






      INFORMATION THEORY


           Today everyone knows how a thermostat works. If
       a house is equipped with a furnace and an air condi-
       tioning unit, both of which operate through a thermo-
       stat, it doesn't take much explaining to understand that
       if the house temperature rises above the desired tem-
0      perature, the thermostat will turn on the air condition-
       er and cool the house again. If the house temperature
       drops too low, the thermostat will turn on the furnace.
           The human mind also operates in this manner. If
       one starts to walk toward a tree on the opposite side
       of a field and then veers to the right,, one glance at the
       tree is all that is required to alter the course back
       toward the tree. If one wanders too far to the left, the
       "thermostat" in the brain will change the course back
       toward the tree just as soon as this information reaches
       the brain through the eyes.
           Thus, it has been discovered that the mind operates
       very much like machines. The process is called "feed-
       back" mechanism-in fact a "negative" feed back-
       negative, because if the temperature rises in a room,
       the information transmitted to the thermostat causes
       the furnace to be shut off so as to reduce the tempera-
       ture, i.e., change it in the opposite direction.
            Almost all of the thought processes can be repro-
       duced by machines. They can be made to calculate
       almost any problem which can be solved by man, but
       in a fraction of the time required of humans. Today
       we have Eniacs and Univacs, or digital and analog
       computers. Their capacity and speed in solving prob-
       lems are simply fabulous.
            It is interesting to note that even imaginative or
       inventive thinking is made possible by some sort of
       a "feed-back" mechanism. Fortunately, wish-thinking
       or ambition is characteristically human. A machine


Dr. G. R. Fitterer


(computer) has no desire or drive to do anything. It
must be fed by human brains. It does not have the
ability to associate the proper thoughts to reach a
logical conclusion. The human brain must first recog-
nize the relationship between, various factors 'before a
problem can be expressed and fed to the machine.
Desire 'and ability to corelate such data must be devel-
oped by young engineers who then would "feed" the
machines which would complete the laborious calcula-
tion. The machines would complete but not understand
or use the answers.
     The impact of information theory, feed-back me-
chanisms, servomechanisms, 'and computers on     the
future trends of science is little realized byv even those
who are skilled in this area.
     One often hears about the rapid changes in tech-
 nology wh;ich have taken place during this century and
 the accelerated pace at which technology has been
 developed since Hiroshima. These are just the begin-
 nings. Every engineer has an association of ideas tucked
 away in the recesses of his mind which, if translated to
 modern computers, would revolutionize some industry
 or science.
     Someone has stated that the 1920's and '30's were
 eras of measurement (i.e., temperature, pressure, time,
 etc.) and that the '40's and'50's were periods of mea-
 surement and the control of processes. However, the
 future will involve eras of synthesis and alterations.
 Machines which err will correct themselves. This is a
 part of the second industrial revolution which has al-
 ready begun.
     Computers and machines have one quality which
 would be of great benefit to the human race. They lack
 the capacity to become frustrated. They solve manly
 problems by trial and error methods and never become
 discouraged when an error is made-they try again-
 and eventually solve the problem. In this respect, if in
 no other, engineers could do well to emulate machines.


