ELECTROLYTIC TINPLATING


BY CHARLES KISER, CH. E. '57


    The growth of electrolytic tinplating was slow
until the outbreak of World War II. Although the
process had been known for many years, the first con-
-tinuous electrolytic tinning unit was not placed in
operation until 1937. Prior to this time, the only method
of tin coating was by immersing the steel sheets into
a bath of molten tin. This was a more economical
operation since the initial cost was lower, and at the
time a hot dip stack did the coating job faster.
     Within the past twenty-five years two events oc-
curred which greatly ichanged several aspects of the tin
plating picture. With the advent of continuous cold
reduction processes in the early thirties continuous
electro-tinning became possible. Then, of course, the
scarcity of tin during World War II imposed strict
standards upon the steel industry forcing them to con-
serve this vital ,metal. Electrolytic tinning with its more
uniform, more accurate coating offered a solution to
this problem.
     Since 1937 the production of electrolytic tin plate
has grown from nothing to the point where eighty
per cent of tin plated products in the United States
and Canada are made by this process. These products.
include tin containers for foods, paints, beverages, oils,
and other types of closures, utensils such as baking pans,
bottle caps, plugs, gaskets and various drawn parts
in toys and electrical equipment.
Methods Of Plating
     The driving force behind the coating operation
is the flow of current between the tin anodes and
the steel strip, the cathode. The current density, and
consequently the amount of coating, may be adjusted
by changing the current or altering the distance be-
tween the tin anodes and the strip. There are three
main methods of plating, called electrolytic lines, each
characterized by the electrolyte used in the plating
bath. They are the vertical acid, halogen, and alkaline


baths. Although the organic electrolytes may differ,
the chemical reaction in the vertical acid and halogen
baths are similar since they both involve the oxidatioh
from metallic tin to the stannous ion (valence of 2) at
the anode and the reverse is true at the cathode. Twice
as great a current density is required in the alkaline
bath since the stannic ion (valence of 4) is involved
in the reaction rather than the stannous ion. This
means that four electrons rather than two must be
liberated to transfer an atom of tin to the steel strip.
It should 'be mentioned that in the vertical acid and
alkaline baths both sides of the strip are coated simult-
eneously while in the halogen bath one side of fhe
strip is coated, the strip is reversed by -passing over
a roller guide, and the other side is then coated. The
vertical acid and halogen baths are highly efficient but
are corrosive to equipment while the alkaline bath is
non-corrosive but less efficient.
     The alkaline plated product is somewhat superior
in corrosion resistance, but lacquers do not adhere to
the product quite as well as the acid products. These
differences have been minimized by -recent advances.
The halogen line requires slightly more floor space as
a result of the horizontal plating. All three lines are
quite suitable as shown, by the large tonnages -produced
by each. Through 1952 there were 15 vertical acid lines,
5 halogen lines and 13 alkaline lines with a combined
capacity of 3,845, tons of tin plate per year.
The Overall Process
     The steel coil to enter the electrolytic line is in-
 spected with respect to shape, hardness, finish, and size.


