    This massive continuous annealing line processes strip
steel at a rate of 1,000 feet per minute to prepare it for
stiffening in the temper mill.


    In this 2-stand temper mill, the steel strip is tempered,
then sheared, or side-trimmed, 'before being coated with tin.


    The annealed, tempered and trimmed s'trip is fed into
this end of the electrolytic tinning line.


  The coating operation follows.
      Two uncoiling reels are generally at the entry end
  of each line. They may be either the standard cone
  type reels or expanding reels. Generally, the reels are
  in series with one reel being charged while the other
  reel is feeding into the line. The reels are charged by
  placing the coil on a platform next to the reel, the
  platform is raised so that the eye of the coil is in line
  with 'the reel, and' then the platform is moved toward
  the reel, so that the reel is inserted into the eye of the
  coil. The platform is then lowered and the reel is ex-
  panded to insure a snug fit.
      The next steps in the process are shearing and
 welding. The head and tail ends of each strip are shear-
 ed by an up-cut shear. The head of the coil to be
 charged is then arc welded to the tail end of the previ-
 'ous coil. The process requires only a few seconds. The
 head of the coil to be charged is engaged in a set of
 pinch rolls which also catches the tail end of the pre-
 vious coil. After the shearing operation   these pinch
 rolls regulate the speeds of the -two coils until the
 seam weld is applied.
     The coil is then fed into the looping pit or tower.
The purpose of the looping pit is to store enough strip
that the line will continue in operation while the weld
is being made. The coil is fed into the looping pit
somewhat faster than! the remainder of the line is run-
ning. Then while the weld is 'being made on the next
coil the line speed may remain constant by using the
excess strip in- the looping pit.
     From the looping pit the coil enters a tension
bridle which provides a sufficient tension on the strip
to prevent the dragging of the strip against any of the
equipment.
     In the two acid type lines an alkaline bath may be
inserted at this point in the process. In the alkaline line
this sometimes is not necessary since the plating bath



