      The plating units are basically similar, differing
  only in the electrolyte used and the number of passes the
  strip makes through the bath. In all cases the strip
  passes over conductor rolls such as chromium plated
  cooper shells mounted on shafts. In alkaline baths the
  anodes are large tin slabs while the anodes in acid
  baths are approximately three inches by four inches by
  six feet long. The life of these anodes depends on the
  amount of current passing through them.
      The plating tanks are generally divided, into four
  compartments. In each of these compartments, the
  strip passes over the contact rolls and into the electro-
  lyte between the banks of anodes. The anodes are add-
  ed from one side of the line and moved through the
  line until they reach the other side of the line. The
  anode bridge slopes slightly toward the strip at the
  anode exit in order to compensate for difference' in
  thickness of anodes. Anodes may be added or sub-
  tracted to control the amount of plating. There are


no cooling worries in an alkaline bath, but in the
