which remove most of the moisture. The remaining
moisture is then removed by hot air heaters. At 'this
point in the process the tin coating is dull and gray in
appearance. By heating the plate just 'above the fusion
point of tin and immediately quenching, the tin be-
comes smoother and more lustrous. This heating is
done by a 'closely regulated current through the strip
much likle the heating that occurs in the filament of a
light bulb.
     After quenching, the strip is given a filming treat-
ment to protect it from rust, discolorations or undesir-
able films. In some operations the plate is immersed in
a chemical solution while other operations use an elec-
trical current and chromic acid to accomplish filming.
In either case a very dense oxide film is created to pro-
tect against further undesirable oxidation.
     The final step before shearing is oiling the strip.
Either emulsion or electrostatic oil-coating may be
employed. In the emulsion method the strip is passed
through a bath or spray of unstable oil emulsion. The
emulsion consists ofan oil, a neutralizing agent, and an
emulsifying agent. Oil content and temperature of the
emulsion control the amount of oil deposited on the
strip. The oil spray is often electrostatically charged and
hence attracted 'to and grounded on the strip in this
menner. When a spray ,met'hod is used, emulsion or
electrostatic, the strip should -pass t'hrough the oiling
unit in a vertical direction.
