COMBUSTION CONTROL

                       BY FRED GLUCKSON, M. E. '58


                         e are now in the age of the automobile horse-
                      power race, and automotive engineers find themselves
                      under continual competitive pressure to build engines
                      of higher and higher horsepower. We are familiar with
                      their methods: higher compression ratios, more efficient
                      carburetion  and valve trains, increased   rotational
                      speeds. Yet the common aims of all of these methods
                      is to burn the maximum amount of gasoline efficiently
                      in a given length of time. It is this efficiency of combus-
                      tion that will become the big engine design criterion.
                      Crankshaft speeds are limited by engine stresses, car-
                      buretion advances are checked by complexity and cost
                      problems, but compression ratio is limited only by the
                      ability of the engine to burn its fuel charge -cleanly and
                      efficiently.
                      Faulty Combustion
                          Thermal efficiency of gasoline increases with com-
                      pression ratio until it levels out at around 14:1. But
                      before this value is reached, tremendous problems arise
                      in controlling the fuel combustion. Faulty burning of
                      the fuel robs power from the engine, decreases fuel
                      mileage and may -severly damage the engine parts. Poor
                      combustion often reaches the stage at which a sharp,
                      audible "knock" is heard upon full throttle acceleration,
                      or upon lugging up a hill. This sound is caused by vi-
                      bration of the combustion chamber parts under severe
                      dynamic loading. If 'allowed to continue, severe knock
                      may even crack a piston.
                          Knock is caused 'by uneven burning of the fuel
                      mixture. The flame front should initiate at ,the spark
                      plub and travel evenly across the combustion chamber.
                      In knock, however, the advancing flame front causes a
                      pressure wave to preceed it to the more remote loca-
                      tions of the fuel 'charge. This pressure wave causes an-
                      other ignition and flame front in another part of the
                      chamber. The two flame fronts, each travelling at 20
                      'to 150 ft./sec., meet and cause a tremendous instan-


SKYSCRAPER ENGINEER




taneous pressure wave. This shock wave strikes the
piston a hammerlike blow.
      Even more severe than knock is a form of com-
 bustion known as pre-ignition. It is caused by the ex-
 istence of a hot spot in the combustion chamber which
 fires the charge before the spark plug itself fires. This
 occurs while the piston is still on the compression stroke
 and creates tremendous pressures to oppose the piston.
 Stresses of great magnitude are thus set up in -piston,
 wrist pin, bearings, and crankshaft. Severe pre-ignition
 has been known to destroy completely an aircraft en-
 gin in seconds.
     Pre-ignition may be set off by a defective, or clog-
 ged cooling system, an exposed spark plug thread, or
 again, by extensive combustion deposite which reduce
 heat transfer to the cooling water or are of such a
 nature that they retain the heat themselves.
 Improving Combustion By Engine Maintenance
     The causes of knock may be eliminated by correct-
 ing any or all of the following conditions.
     The distributor timing is advanced as far as possi-
ble to get maximum power out of the gasoline. But the
effect of the vacuum distributor advance must also 'be
considered. When the engine is operating at full throt-
tle, as in the two previous situations, an additional
spark advance of 10 to 15 crankshaft degrees is realiz-
ed. Thus too high of an initial spark advance may make
an engine prone to knock.
     A new engine may operate smoothly under all con-
ditions, but when some additional mileage is recorded
it may begin to knock. This is due to deposits 'which
form naturally in all cars, and which are a factor in
engine knock. Occasional high speed driving will help
keep an engine free of these deposits.
     A too lean carburetor setting or float level may
boost economy, but lean fuel mixtures are more apt to
knock than rich ones.
     The causes for surface ignition can be eliminated
by improving cooling, removal of all sharp edges within
the combustion chamber, proper spark plug selection
and cleaning, improved valve maintenance, and the re-


