   Combustion-Control Additives
       Possibly the most widely used fuel additive is
  tetraethyl lead. The addition of small quantities of
  TEL will greatly boost the anti-knock quality of gaso-
  line. In opposition to this beneficial quality are certain
  drawbacks to the use of TEL. It is quite expensive. It
  is 'highly toxic, and so is limited in concentration to 3
  -cc. per gallon of gas by Federal law. This law also re-
  quires that all fuels using TEL indicate this fact by
  also adding a red dye. TEL has a tendency to form
  undesirable lead deposits in the combustion chamber,
  and so necessitates the use of ethylene dibromide as a
  scavenging 'agent. However, TEL is a very flexible
  agent for boosting octane rating, and has found 'wide
  use in refining.
      Another additive for controlling undesirable com-
 bus'tion (knock) is ICC or Ignition Control Compound.
 This phosphorous compound has three major effects.
 It prevents carbon deposits in the combustion chamber
 from becoming incandescent and causing preignition.
 It prevents spark plugs from fouling due to deposits.
 By suppressing preignition, it lowers octane require-
 ment to that needed 'to suppress ordinary knock.
     Other combustion control compounds added to
gasoline are benzol and alcohol, but these are rarely
used because of 'certain important disadvantages.
     Thus, the performance of tomorrow's advanced
design engines is limited by the ability of tomorrow's
gasolines to burn with a maximum of heat output, and
in controlled, smooth combustion. i


