"IT WILL FLY"


     Professor Langley taught physics and astronomy
 at the University (then kncwn as the Western Univer-
 sity of Pennsylvania). He was also director of the
 Allegheny Observatory, serving in this capacity for
 twenty years from 1867 to 1887. During this time he
 attracted wide acclaim for his writings and general
 contributions to astronomy.
     But in 1866 Professor Langley became interested
 in a work on the flight of migratory whooping cranes
 by Israel Lancaster. The 52-year-old professor was in-
 stantly fired with curiosity to find the secret of the
 gentle soaring flight of the great birds who could sus-
 tain themselves for hours in a seemingly effortless posi-
 tion. This curiosity launched the aging professor on a
 long hard road of research which led down one blind
 alley after another, and finally ended in defeat.
     Langley set about to determine what forces in the
 air the birds used to sustain themselves, not realizing
 that the balance of forces and the power of the flight
 was controlled by the birds and not by the air around
 them. By means of a rapidly rotating table, on which
 were mounted stuffed birds with their wings extended,
 Langley was able to measure lift and to some extent
 drag.
     Realizing -that the flight of these birds was depend-
ent upon a Newtonian maxim which stated that the
resistance of a plane surface to the air varies as the
square of the sine of its angle of incidence. Langley
began to expand his experiments and apply the princi-
ple to a variety of surfaces.
     With the backing of William Thaw, a Pittsburgh
philanthropist, Langley built a larger spinning table
with brass plates attached to the ends of long arms. The
plates, which could be rotated on their longitudinal
axes, would provide a varying angle of attack.
Finds Error In Newton's Law (can be rewarded)
     The result of this study was the issuance of a
physical law by Langley which stated that Newton's
figures on resistance were in error 'and that resistance
was only 1/20 that stated by Newton. He further stated
that mechanical flight was possible with engines then in
existance.


Samuel Pierpont Langley


BY JIM MARINO, COL. '58


     In 1889 Professor Langley was named secretary of
 the Smithsonian Institute in Washington, D. C. As a
 result of this position, Professor Langley was able to
 secure funds to publish his writings on heavier-than-
 air flight. Also at this time Langley experimented with
 hundreds of flying models powered by many engines of
 various kinds. He was forced to end these toy-like
 experiments without having attained a single flight of
 more than four seconds.
     Unwanted publicity hounded Langley throughout
 his experiments and followed him unceasingly to his
 retirement. The love he had for quiet research and the
 need for solitude presented by his work at the institute
 were denied him. He was a watched man from the
 very beginning of his experiments. This publicity would
 have made him a national hero had his experiments
culminated in manned flight. Instead, public acclaim
turned to ridicule and caused -the destruction of his
dream of powered flight.

