      If Professor Langley had actually concluded his
 experiments with the attainment of powered flight, his
 achievement would have made him an internationally-
 acclaimed pioneer of aerodynamics. He would have
 been known as the man who achieved successful, heav-
 ier-than-air flight seven years before the first manned
 flight -by the Wright brothers. But circumstances were
 to shape the destiny of his later years. Already the
 enraged press was screaming in black type for the
 start of the Spanish-American War.
 War Contract Offered
     In July,. 1898, Gene Adolphus W. Greely, chief of
 the United States Army Signal Corps, was sent to
 Smithsonian -from President McKinley to request that
 Langley build an aerodrome suitable for combat duty.
 The weary professor rissisted and restated his desire to
 close his book of flight research. But the army had ?dif-
 ferent.,ideas. After securing a sum of $50,000 to cover
 the expense of building a manned aerodrome, Professor
 Langley reluctantly agreed.
     Experiments were begun      in June; 1898. Mr.
 Charles M. Manly, a Cornell University graduate, was
 appointed to design a full-scale airframe, capable of
 carrying a man. The models used in 1896 were scaled
 up and used in experimental flights from the houseboat
 in the Potomac. Throughout 1899, the experiments
 were unsuccessful. Trouble plagued the houseboat, the
 catapult, and the aerodromes themselves.
     Two years before, a contract had been signed with
S. M. Balzer fortwo lightweight gasoline engines of
twelve horsepower, weighing 'less' than 220 pounds.
Balzer never met the contract. Langley spent six weeks
in Europe trying to secure engines of this type without
success. Finally, Manly designed and built a 5-cylinder,
4 cycle radial engine, weighing 207.47 pounds and de-
livering 52.4 horsepower.
     By the summer of 1903, the tandem-winged aero-
drome, with a wing span of 48 feet and an overall
length of 5'2 feet, was ready to be launched. It boasted
a framework. of steel tu'bing, bevel gear transmission,
cotton-percaline-covered wings and two pusher propell-
ers. It weighed 850 pounds 'with the pilot. The aero-
drome used a split-vane rutter and an "equilibrium
control," which trimmed the ship fore and aft. The
pilot was able to adjust the engine in flight from  his


