 Manly and said, "I must congratulate them." But the
 fire of curiosity and the burning desire to achieve
 powered flight were gone from Langley's eyes. He
 cleared his desk in the Smithsonian Institute and re-
 signed his position.
     On February 27, 1906, without fanfare or public
attention, forgotten :by the press which beat him to
defeat and the crowds that waited to see him fail, Pro-
fessor Langley died. He had never seen a man fly.
     In 1914, a rebuilt model of the man-carrying aero-
 drome was successfully flown and landed on the waters
 of the Potomac, proving too' late to the world that
 Professor Langley had achieved his dream  and that
only the world prevented him from seeing it. E


