 training and with your success as his goal.
      I think the reason that engineering has reached
 the status of a profession is two-fold. First, we are
 more dependent on technology today than we were
 twenty or thirty years ago. We might think of the
 world today without some of the recent technological
 'advances. Picture our day without any plastics, super
 highways, or electronics. I won't try to justify the pre-
 sent complexity of our lives with these 'things, but we
 have found them useful enough to become dependent
 on them. The non-engineering public realizes the need
 for the special background, th special type of thinking
 that's necessary to keep pace with this complexity.
     The second reason for the elevation of the engin-
eers to a professional status comes from  within the
engineering group. Although the need for engineers
has existed for quite a few years, people will not raise
any group to the status of a profession unless they
trust that group  without reservation. Fortunately,
there is a segment of trained engineers that has estab-
lished, promoted, and lived by a written code of ethics
and a personal integrity that the public has come to


SKYSCRAPER ENGINEER













































trust. This has elevated engineeers as a whole to the
professional level.
     It is unfortunate that we also have a segment of
engineers who still consider themselves highly skilled
tradesmen. Today we hear a lot of talk about the
engineering unions. I firmly believe that there is a
place for an engineering union. However, this engin-
eering union should only serve that segment of men with
an engineering training that should be catagorized as
engineering technicians. For that large group of en-
gineering technicians, the union is a necessity. For
the professional engineer, the creative engineer, there
is no need for anything more than the present profes-
sional and technical societies.
     Apparantly the consensus of the many studies of
our manpower shortage indicate that we should use our
trained people more wisely. We should emphasize the
creative engineering and the technician level as two
separate branches. Certainly, there is a need for tech-
nically trained people to do the many necessary jobs
to bring an idea to fruition. The technician does not,
however, have the same responsibility as that of the
person originating the idea or directing the work. Their
training need not be as extensive as that necessary for


the creative engineer, the professional.
     If a student wants to work in the Engineeering
Profession and not as a technician, he must begin to ac-
quire the professional attitude early. The acquisition of
the characteristics, standards or methods of profession-
als is what I would call "Professionalism." Since there
is no place in the curriculum for professionalism, the
student must get it for himself.
     At a college a student can learn the the funda-
mental physical laws. The techniques of adapting these
physical laws to produce or to construct for the com-
mon good may be learned in an engineering school.
The use of this special knowledge is like playing ball.
We 'may learn the physical law that a ball tossed in
the air will fall toward the ground. In engineering
school we would go further, we learn the technique
of how to catch ,the ball. Now to bring the analogy a
little further, 'com'pare the catching of the ball by the
sand-lot player to that of the professional ball player
Both perform the same feat, but we enjoy watching the
professional. We pay 'to see the professional ball player
because he catches the ball with ease, gracefulness, pre-
cision, and much respect for the game.
      I believe that a student can start early in becoming
 a Professional Engineer by following three simple rules:
     1. Respect your profession; Utilize your time well
        in school to get the best possible training in
        your field. Be prepared to participate whole-
        heartedly in professional and learned societies.
     2. Respect others; They deserve that you give your
         best, that means your best work, your best ap-
         pearance, your best language. Be prepared to
         be humble, personally I have never met a man,
         no matter what his background or job might be,
         from  whom   I could not learn something of
         value.
     3. Respect yourself; Be honest in evaluating your
         technical ability, the a'mount of time you spend
         on your studies, your habits. You will find that
         you have the. same opportunities as the best,
         and the same abilities.
      It is rather obvious that I have been concentrating
  on developing the value of appearance, use of correct
  English, and attitude to the Professional Engineer.
  These things alone are not enough, by any means, to
  elevate a person to the professional status. We certainly
  need many other things such as hard work, decisiveness,
  dependability, along with perfection in creative engin-
  eering. This idea of creating     good impressions is
  important. It's a simple thing to accomplish, yet it
  means so much to a practicing engineer. We can't force
  our services on the general public, they must ask for
  our help or advice. So, before we can make a "Contri-
  bution" as President Eisenhower put it, before we
  can do our work for the benefit of non-engineers, we
  must have their trust and respect. I think we 'may
  help win that trust and respect with professionalism. 0


