TECHNICAL WRITING


          Industry needs engineers who like
        to write. How does technical writing
        and editing compare as a career for
        an engineer who can write? How
        broad is the field? What does it take
        to be a technical writer?








    Engineering recruiters are now asking specifically
'for engineers who like to write. Technical writing, al-
most unheard of twenty years ago, is today a multi-
million dollar industry. A new form of exposition?
Certainly not! Technical writing was born in the dawn
of technology. Actually, most early technical writing
took the form of patent applications in which a gadget
was described in purpose, construction, and operation.
Later, it was usually the inventor himself who wrote
the first instruction booklets. World War II saw the
need for voluminous amounts of technical literature.
The armed forces required operation, maintenance, and
repair manuals to instruct its personnel in the care and
feeding of weapons, machines, and electronic apparatus.


  BY      JOSEPH SCHULER, E. E.'57








Today, as the complexity of equipment has greatly
increased, military services have even greater need for
better written and more complete instruction manuals.
The Importance of Technical Writing
    It is not only the military who is dependent on
good technical writing. To a great degree, the scientific
and engineering professions are tied to the excellence of
its technical publications. Industry would be seriously
hampered without it. As the complexilty of modem tech-
nology has increased, the need 'for technical communi-
cation has gained prominence and importance. To. in-
sure high quality publications, many industrial and re-
search organizations maintain a separate staff of per-
sonnel to prepare, write, and edit technical information.
The plain fact of the matter is 'that reducing newly
found knowledge to a useable form is as important
as the discovery itself.
Forms of Technical Writing


SKYSCRAPER ENGINEER




     Technical writing has as many forms as there are
needs and purpose in a complicated industrial age. The
more common forms are the technical letter and bro-
chure, the engineering report and proposal, and the
technical manual. Equally important are the articles
which appear in the scientific and engineering journals
and the familiar trade magazine's. All good technical
writing, no matter what its final form, affectively trans-
lates specialized  information  into language   under-
standable by a specific audience. To be effective, this
writing must be clear, concise, complete, and consist-
ent with the primary requirement of accuracy.
Technical Writing Opportunities
     Engineers who like to write can select from a wide
variety of opportunities. These opportunities will often
carry different descriptive titles. However, whether he
be a technical editor, a publications engineer, engin-
eering writer, or scientific correspondent, all have the
responsibility of transforming technical data into tech-
nical information for the specific reader. However,
techPi'cal writing opportunities may be classified accord-
ing to specific writing requirements:
  1. Writing which contains specialized information
      detailed in engineering and scientific fact.
           This writing is prepared by highly skilled
           engineers and    scientists whose complete
           knowledge of what is involved permits him
           to explain accurately and concisely the in-
           nards of mysterious black 'boxes. Writers in
           this category are sometimes called Product
           Technical Writers or Engineering Writers.
           Since their writing must be complete and
           accurate, they must fully understand the
           details of 'the product or process. This un-
           derstanding of detail is the "little picture"
           aspect of technical writing.
             Oftentimes writers in this category work
           in groups preparing instruction books., main-
           tenance and operating manuals for com-
           plex products or systems. These writers, fully
           aware of their audience, must choose the
           proper language symbol to bridge the gap
           between manufacturer and customer. The
           language symbol which adequately describ-
           es a product, idea, or proposal may often
           be by algebra, differential equations, charts,
           diagrams, or cartoons. The product writers
           must also include ,the "how and the why"
           behind the apparatus being described. In
           addition, his information must be concise,
           clear, and within the grasp and experience
           of his readers.
  2. Writing with varying amounts of engineering con-
     ten't and a more general readership.
           These opportunities generally fall in the
           category of Technical Publicity. Those who
           prepare articles in this classification are
           called  Technical Editors or Publications
           Engineer. In general, these engineering jour-
           nalists are required to prepare, write and


           edit technical information   for the trade
           magazines or house organs. They are as-
           signed to a division or specific area where
           research is going on. They personally estab-
           lish contact with those performing the work
           and keep fully -abreast with the development.
           They seek items of interest to readers of
           the trade and technical journals. Not only
           do they gather information, prepare -the
           write-ups, but also plan the publicity and
           direct the taking of photographs. In short,
           the Technical Editor works with a story
           from concept through actual printing and
           proof-reading.
  3. Writing which contains      technical information
     slanted toward sales promotion and advertising.
           Technical trained writers in this category
           plan, create, and execute advertising and
           sales promotion programs. These men have
           the broad responsibility which directly ef-
           fects the sales of company products. MCich
           of their writing borders .the field of public
           relations.
     The opportunities mentioned above are only a few
of the writing assignments available in a world where
scientific discovery is common place. Other opportun-
ities include science writing for newspapers a*nd maga-
zines, science writing for television and radio, and free-
lance technical writing. Editors everywhere are com-
plaining about not having enough suitable science copy.
The broad field of science writing offers unlimited
opportunity to the writer who can interpret technical
achievements in common terms understandable to the
man on the street.
Qualifications Of A Technical Writer
     Just as technical writing varies in form and in
engineering content so do the qualifications of the writ-


