er. Technical training is however considered to be a
prime requisite. Many companies insist that a man have
had formal engineering training or extensive experience.
Graduate engineers with industrial background are
'highly desirable. It is important that the writer gain
the confidence of those engineers actually engaged in
the project. Since these engineers are his chief source of
information, he must be able to talk their language.
Technical training also implies that the writer must be
able to think. Organized t:hought, before, during, and
after the writing process, is essential for intelligent
writing. Organized thinking is difficult, and this is per-
haps the main trouble with any writer. He must de-
cide which ideas are important, which can be left out,
which need explanation, and which do not.
     Another important qualification is journalistic skill.
The writer must be able to write simply, factually, and
interestingly. In order to express himself clearly, he
must have facility in handling words. The purpose of
every technical communication is 'to convey ideas and
information accurately and efficiently. This objective
requires that the writing be brief and easily under-
stood. It is also important that the technical writer
enjoy his work. He must like to write. Words are his
tools and he should use them with pleasure and skill.
     Other qualifications are originality, imagination,
and a healthy curiosity. The effectiveness of the writing
is greatly increased if it is pleasant, forceful, and easy
to read. In order that the article possess life and in-
terest, the writer must be original and imaginative. He
must also be able to sense a potential story which will
appeal to his audience. This quality is sometimes call-
ed having a "nose for news".
     A  friendly personality is another   qualification
which measures 'to a large degree the success of a
Technical writer. The writer must radiate confidence
and win friends. He must also employ a considerable


amount of tact and diplomacy in dealing with busy
scientists and engineers. In order to obtain accurate
and complete information, he must cooperate and plan
his personal contacts for convenience of others. These
attributes are of course important in any organization-
al activity.
Advantages Of A Technical Writing Career
     Each phase of engineering, research, development,
 production, or sales has its advantages and attractions.
 Each offers the engineer the opportunity for profes-
 sional development. This is particularly true in the
 field of technical writing. An excellent way of contin-
 uing his education, it enables the writer to keep fully
 informed in 'the area of his interest. Assignments re-
 quire the writing engineer to observe first hand the
 research, design, development, production, and opera-
 tion of a product or process. This over all scope of
 writing assignments is known as the "big picture"
 aspect of technical writing. Engineers today are becom-
 ing more and more specialized. However, the diverse
 nature of his work excludes the possibility of a writer
 becoming pigionholed, or specialized on one chassis
 one function, or one subassembly. In addition, techni-
 cal assignments call for association with leading author-
 ities in various fields. Information from the best minds
 in science and engineering passes through the writer's
 hands. From -the journalistic point of view, technical
 writing offers an outlet for written expression plus the
 satisfaction of adding to the world's storehouse of
 technical information. It also offers an opportunity to
 travel, and to attend important meetings. In addition
 ito these advantages, the salary range is comparable
 to other kinds of engineering.
     For those trained in engineering and science and
skilled in the art of writing, technical writing offers
unlimited opportunity. It is an open invitation and
,challenge for engineers to grow in t'heir profession. N


